resource.name: SDOT Street Use Sign-In Data
resource.description: Data from Seattle Department of Transportation Street Use Division Applicant Services Sign In system. Data collection started in May 2009. Data is used to run the SUSI application, which alerts permit reviewers by type of review that an applicant is at the counter. Applicants come to the counter to pay fees, get coaching, apply for permits, and extend permits for a wide variety of private uses of the right of way. The data can be used to calculate changes over time for visit volumes, volumes by category, wait times, and service times. Wait time data prior to 2013 is unreliable. Check-in categories changed in July 2013 and February 2014. Category information is unreliable prior to February 2014. Prior to that February 2014, customers self-selected the category. Post February 2014, screeners selected the category.
resource.attribution: City of Seattle Department of Transportation Street Use Division
columns_description: Raw data: Time customer reached by permit reviewer. End of Wait time. Start of Service time. (Socrata does not recognize this as a time field. Format: h:mm:ss AM/PM)
Raw data: Date customer reached by permit reviewer.
Raw data: If the service category is "Meeting," this is the Street Use or Urban Forestry employee that the visitor is meeting with.
Raw data: Unique ID for visit. Primary Key.
Raw data: Time customer signed into system. Start of Wait Time. (Socrata does not recognize this as a time field. Format: h:mm:ss AM/PM)
Raw data: Time customer finished with permit reviewer. End of Service Time. (Socrata does not recognize this as a time field. Format: h:mm:ss AM/PM)
Calculated field: TimeCompletedTime minus TimeReachedTime in minutes.
Calculated field: TimeReachedTime minus TimeInTime in minutes.
Raw data: Date customer finished working with permit reviewer.
Raw data: Date customer signed into system.
Calculated field: Week number where Monday is day 1 of the week. Some years end up with 53 weeks and some have no year 1.

Raw data: Visit reasons updated in July 2013 and February 2014. Prior to February 2014, visitors self-selected. Post February 2014, qualified screeners made the selections. Data unreliable prior to February 2014. Exclude Staff Use Only -- this checks visitors in for screening. After screening, customers are signed back in for the a specific visit reason. Counting both would inflate visit counts. Visitors may check in more than once for other categories since they may need to see multiple reviewer types depending on the complexity of their project(s).

Calculated field: Exclude from wait time calculations. Calculates TimeReachedTime minus TimeInTime and assumes that if this is greater than 9 hours (the number of hours the counter is open), someone did not click a button and the data is in error. Also returns "Exclude" if the TimeReachedTime is blank.
Calculated field: Calculates TimeCompletedTime minus TimeReachedTime in hours. Used for calculating service times longer than 2 hours.
Calculated field: Calculates TimeReachedTime minus TimeInTime. Used to calculate wait times greater than two hours.
Calculated field: Was the customer's wait or service time greater than 2 hours?
Calculated field: Time waiting for meetings does not reflect applicant services team performance. Exclude meetings from calculations.

Calculated field: Exclude from service time calculations. Calculates TimeCompletedTime minus TimeReachedTime and assumes that if this is greater than 9 hours (the number of hours the counter is open), someone did not click a button and the data is in error. Also returns "Exclude" if the TimeCompletedTime is blank.

Raw data: Status of the customer at the time the data was last uploaded. If the date is more than a day older than the data and the status is not Completed, a button was not clicked. All visitors leave Street Use by 5:00 PM each day.
Raw data: Unique ID for Visit reason (category). Foreign key.

resource.name: Key Measure: Capital Projects - Percent of capital projects on budget
resource.description: A project is considered 'on-budget' when the total project cost is projected to be the same or below the current adopted budget in the Capital Improvement Program (CIP)

resource.name: Key Measure: 40% of hours worked (on specific City of Seattle managed projects) are performed by workers from economically distressed ZIP codes by 2025
resource.description: In 2015, the City began implementing a master Community Workforce Agreement (CWA). The agreement prioritizes the hiring of residents from economically distressed neighborhoods of Seattle and King County, women, and people of color on City construction projects over $5 million. This data set reflects the percentage of annual priority hire hours worked by residents living in economically distressed ZIP codes.

resource.name: Key Measure: Residents subscribed to AlertSeattle
New City Regulated Affordable homes coming online 2019-2022
resource.description: This tile measures new City Regulated Affordable Housing. These are affordable homes regulated as rent and income restricted, through regulatory agreements with the City of Seattle Office of Housing including: City Funding from Office of Housing, Multifamily Tax Exemption program (MFTE), Incentive Zoning (IZ), and Mandatory Housing Affordability (MHA). IZ and MHA create affordable units in market rate buildings.
